# Chapter 4 - Choosing Technologies Across the Data Engineering Lifecycle

## Definition
Technology choices are tactical decisions that bring your architecture to life.
Architecture is the what, why, and when.
Technology is the how.
Always get your architecture right before choosing your tools.

## The Most Important Rule
- Architecture first, technology second
- Never choose tools before you have a clear architecture
- Does this technology add value to the data product and the business?

## Key Considerations When Choosing Technology
1. Team size and capabilities - match tools to your team's skills and bandwidth
2. Speed to market - deliver value early and often, perfect is the enemy of good
3. Interoperability - tools must connect and work well together
4. Cost optimization - evaluate TCO, TOCO, and FinOps before committing
5. Immutable vs transitory - build on tools that stand the test of time
6. Location - on premises, cloud, hybrid, or multicloud
7. Build vs buy - buy by default, build only for competitive advantage
8. Monolith vs modular - prefer modular and loosely coupled systems
9. Serverless vs servers - start serverless, move to servers when you outgrow it

## Key Insight
Immutable technologies like SQL, Python, Bash, and object storage
will outlast most of the shiny new tools that come and go.
The Lindy Effect says the longer a technology has been around,
the longer it will continue to be used. Invest in the fundamentals.

## Cost Terms to Know
- TCO - Total Cost of Ownership, all direct and indirect costs
- TOCO - Total Opportunity Cost, what you gave up by choosing this tool
- Capex - large up-front investment, avoid where possible
- Opex - pay as you go, preferred approach in the cloud

## Build vs Buy
- Default to open source and managed services
- Build only when it creates a genuine competitive advantage
- OSS - free community maintained tools like Airflow and dbt
- COSS - managed commercial versions like Databricks and dbt Cloud

## Key Terms I Learned
- Immutable technology - stands the test of time (SQL, S3, Linux, Python)
- Transitory technology - comes and goes (most frameworks and platforms)
- Lindy Effect - older technology is likely to stick around longer
- Cargo-cult engineering - copying big tech without having their resources
- Data gravity - once data is in a cloud it is expensive to move out
- Lift and shift - moving servers to cloud without optimising for cloud
- COSS - Commercial Open Source Software
- Serverless - running code without managing infrastructure
- Distributed monolith - distributed system with all the problems of a monolith

## What This Means for Me
I already use Airflow, dbt, and AWS in my projects which are
exactly the kinds of modular, interoperable tools this chapter recommends.
I need to focus on understanding the cost and trade-offs of each tool
and always ask whether a technology adds real value to the business
before adopting it. Fundamentals like SQL and Python will always matter more
than chasing the latest tool or framework.